oai_dc:dc.dc:title: Highland Hospital Cadet Nursing Class of 1944
oai_dc:dc.dc:description:
Thirteen women comprised the cadet nursing class of 1944 at the Highland Hospital School of Nursing. Established in 1943 under the Bolton Act, the United States Cadet Nurse Corps was created to promote the profession and ensure that there were an adequate number of professionally trained nurses to provide care for American citizens both at home and those on the battlefront during World War II. Participants were required to pledge themselves to serve as military or civilian nurses during the war.

Cadets received scholarships for nursing education, a monthly stipend, and a distinctive uniform to wear in public. For the first nine months of their education, students were known as precadet nurses. The next fifteen to twenty months was referred to them as junior cadets, followed by senior cadet nurses. In order to maintain eligibility, nursing school programs were required to accelerate their programs, making them twenty-four to thirty months.

Cadet Nurse Oath: At this moment of my induction into the United States Cadet Nurse Corps of the United States Public Health Service: I am solemnly aware of the obligations I assume toward my country and toward my chosen profession; I will follow faithfully the teachings of my instructors and the guidance of the physicians with whom I work; I will hold in trust the finest traditions of nursing and the spirit of the Corps; I will keep my body strong, my mind alert, and my heart steadfast; I will be kind, tolerant, and understanding; Above all, I will dedicate myself now and forever to the triumph of life over death. As a Cadet Nurse, I pledge to my country my service in essential nursing for the duration of the war.

The program was supervised by the United States Public Health Service Division of Nursing Education, and ended in 1948.

Sources: http://www.cadetnurse.com/Welcome.html
http://uscadetnurse.org/
Petry, Lucile. “U.S. Cadet Nurse Corps: Established under the Bolton Act” The American Journal of Nursing, Volume 43, No. 8, Aug., 1943), pages 704-708.

Uniforms are gray & white, per the September 1944 edition of the Highland Bulletin.
